---
<div class="two-col">
  <div style="background:var(--faint);border:1.5px solid var(--border);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1rem">
    <div style="font-family:var(--ff-disp);font-size:.95rem;font-weight:600;color:var(--accent);margin-bottom:.5rem">Lever 1 — Snail selection</div>
    <div style="font-family:var(--ff-body);font-size:.88rem;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.68">
      Younger, smaller snails produce a higher ratio of MBI relative to DBI.
      Both precursor types are present in all snails — the ratio differs by sex,
      age, and season. Selecting for younger snails at the sourcing stage
      increases the MBI content of the dye before any processing begins.
    </div>

  </div>
  <div style="background:var(--faint);border:1.5px solid var(--border);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1rem">
    <div style="font-family:var(--ff-disp);font-size:.95rem;font-weight:600;color:var(--accent);margin-bottom:.5rem">Lever 2 — Temperature</div>
    <div style="font-family:var(--ff-body);font-size:.88rem;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.68">
      60°C in water activates MBI thermochromism → shifts toward blue.<br/>
      100°C (full boiling) activates DBI thermochromism → shifts toward red-purple.<br/>
      Temperature selectively activates one compound's shift while leaving the other
      relatively unchanged — giving precise color control at the finishing stage.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
